attributes.value: [0001] ### A Next-Generation Smart Contract and Decentralized Application Platform
[0003] In the last few months, there has been a great
[0004] amount of interest into the area of using
[0005] Bitcoin-like blockchains - the mechanism that
[0006] allows for the entire world to agree on the state
[0007] of a public ownership database - for more than
[0008] just money. Commonly cited applications include
[0009] using on-blockchain digital assets to represent
[0010] custom currencies and financial instruments
[0011] (['colored coins'](https://docs.google.com/a/buterin.com/document/d/1AnkP_cVZTCMLIzw4DvsW6M8Q2JC0lIzrTLuoWu2z1BE/edit)),
[0012] ['smart property'](https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Smart_Property)
[0013] devices such as cars which track a colored coin on
[0014] a blockchain to determine their present legitimate
[0015] owner, as well as more advanced applications such
[0016] as decentralized exchange, financial derivatives,
[0017] peer-to-peer gambling and on-blockchain identity
[0018] and reputation systems. Perhaps the most ambitious
[0019] of all cited applications is the concept of
[0020] autonomous agents or
[0021] [decentralized autonomous organizations](http://bitcoinmagazine.com/7050/bootstrapping-a-decentralized-autonomous-corporation-part-i/)
[0022] (DAOs) - autonomous entities that operate on the
[0023] blockchain without any central control whatsoever,
[0024] eschewing all dependence on legal contracts and
[0025] organizational bylaws in favor of having resources
[0026] and funds autonomously managed by a self-enforcing
[0027] smart contract on a cryptographic blockchain.
[0029] However, most of these applications are difficult
[0030] to implement today, simply because the scripting
[0031] systems of Bitcoin, and even next-generation
[0032] cryptocurrency protocols such as the Bitcoin-based
[0033] colored coins protocol and so-called 'metacoins',
[0034] are far too limited to allow the kind of
[0035] arbitrarily complex computation that DAOs require.
[0036] What this project intends to do is take the
[0037] innovations that such protocols bring, and
[0038] generalize them - create a fully-fledged,
[0039] Turing-complete (but heavily fee-regulated)
[0040] cryptographic ledger that allows participants to
[0041] encode arbitrarily complex contracts, autonomous
[0042] agents and relationships that will be mediated
[0043] entirely by the blockchain. Rather than being
[0044] limited to a specific set of transaction types,
[0045] users will be able to use Ethereum as a sort of
[0046] 'Lego of crypto-finance' - that is to say, one
[0047] will be able to implement any feature that one
[0048] desires simply by coding it in the protocol's
[0049] internal scripting language. Custom currencies,
[0050] financial derivatives, identity systems and
[0051] decentralized organizations will all be easy to
[0052] do, but more importantly, unlike previous systems,
[0053] it will also be possible to construct transaction
[0054] types that even the Ethereum developers did not
[0055] imagine. Altogether, we believe that this design
[0056] is a solid step toward the realization of
[0057] 'cryptocurrency 2.0'; we hope that Ethereum will
[0058] be as significant an addition to the
[0059] cryptocurrency ecosystem as the advent of Web 2.0
[0060] was to the static-content-only internet of 1999.

[0093] ## Why A New Platform?
[0095] When one wants to create a new application,
[0096] especially in an area as delicate as cryptography
[0097] or cryptocurrency, the immediate, and correct,
[0098] first instinct is to use existing protocols as
[0099] much as possible. There is no need to create a new
[0100] currency, or even a new protocol, when the problem
[0101] can be solved entirely by using existing
[0102] technologies. Indeed, the puzzle of attempting to
[0103] solve the problems of
[0104] [smart property](https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Smart_Property),
[0105] [smart contracts](https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Contracts)
[0106] and [decentralized autonomous corporations](http://bitcoinmagazine.com/7050/bootstrapping-a-decentralized-autonomous-corporation-part-i/)
[0107] on top of Bitcoin is how our interest in
[0108] next-generation cryptocurrency protocols
[0109] originally started. Over the course of our
[0110] research, however, it became evident that while
[0111] the Bitcoin protocol is more than adequate for
[0112] currency, basic multisignature escrow and certain
[0113] simple versions of smart contracts, there are
[0114] fundamental limitations that make it non-viable
[0115] for anything beyond a certain very limited scope
[0116] of features.
[0119] ### Colored Coins
[0121] The first attempt to implement a system for
[0122] managing smart property and custom currencies and
[0123] assets on top of a blockchain was built as a sort
[0124] of overlay protocol on top of Bitcoin, with many
[0125] advocates making a comparison to the way that, in
[0126] the [internet protocol stack](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite),
[0127] [HTTP](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol)
[0128] serves as a layer on top of
[0129] [TCP](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transmission_Control_Protocol).
[0130] The [colored coins](https://docs.google.com/a/ursium.com/document/d/1AnkP_cVZTCMLIzw4DvsW6M8Q2JC0lIzrTLuoWu2z1BE/edit)
[0131] protocol is roughly defined as follows:
[0133] 1. A colored coin issuer determines that a given
[0134] transaction output H:i (H being the transaction
[0135] hash and `i` the output index) represents a
[0136] certain asset, and publishes a 'color definition'
[0137] specifying this transaction output alongside what
[0138] it represents (eg. 1 satoshi from `H:i` = 1 ounce
[0139] of gold redeemable at Stephen's Gold Company)
[0140] 2. Others 'install' the color definition file in
[0141] their colored coin clients.
[0142] 3. When the color is first released, output H:i is
[0143] the only transaction output to have that color.
[0144] 4. If a transaction spends inputs with color X,
[0145] then its outputs will also have color X. For
[0146] example, if the owner of H:i immediately makes a
[0147] transaction to split that output among five
[0148] addresses, then those transaction outputs will all
[0149] also have color X. If a transaction has inputs of
[0150] different colors, then a 'color transfer rule' or
[0151] 'color kernel' determines which colors which
[0152] outputs are (eg. a very naive implementation may
[0153] say that output 0 has the same color as input 0,
[0154] output 1 the same color as input 1, etc).
[0155] 5. When a colored coin client notices that it
[0156] received a new transaction output, it uses a
[0157] back-tracing algorithm based on the color kernel
[0158] to determine the color of the output. Because the
[0159] rule is deterministic, all clients will agree on
[0160] what color (or colors) each output has.
[0162] However, the protocol has several fundamental
[0163] flaws:
[0166] **Simplified Payment Verification in Bitcoin**
[0168] ![d57c68929cbc33ed0974cdc02a6e87246810cf8a8b78002ee2c5b3ed90a6ee4d](img/spv_bitcoin.png)
[0170] _Left: it suffices to present only a small number
[0171] of nodes in a Merkle tree to give a proof of the
[0172] validity of a branch._
[0174] _Right: any attempt to change any part of the
[0175] Merkle tree will eventually lead to an
[0176] inconsistency somewhere up the chain._
[0179] 1. **Difficulty of simplified payment
[0180] verification** - Bitcoin's
[0181] [Merkle Tree](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merkle_tree)
[0182] construction allows for a protocol known as
[0183] '[simplified payment verification](https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Scalability#Simplified_payment_verification)',
[0184] where a client that does not download the full
[0185] blockchain can quickly determine the validity of a
[0186] transaction output by asking other nodes to
[0187] provide a cryptographic proof of the validity of a
[0188] single branch of the tree. The client will still
[0189] need to download the block headers to be secure,
[0190] but the amount of data bandwidth and verification
[0191] time required drops by a factor of nearly a
[0192] thousand. With colored coins, this is much harder.
[0193] The reason is that one cannot determine the color
[0194] of a transaction output simply by looking up the
[0195] Merkle tree; rather, one needs to employ the
[0196] backward scanning algorithm, fetching potentially
[0197] thousands of transactions and requesting a Merkle
[0198] tree validity proof of each one, before a client
[0199] can be fully satisfied that a transaction has a
[0200] certain color. After over a year of investigation,
[0201] including help from ourselves, no solution has
[0202] been found to this problem.
[0203] 2. **Incompatibility with scripting** - as
[0204] mentioned above, Bitcoin does have a moderately
[0205] flexible scripting system, for example allowing
[0206] users to sign transactions of the form 'I release
[0207] this transaction output to anyone willing to pay
[0208] to me 1 BTC'. Other examples include
[0209] [assurance contracts](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assurance_contract),
[0210] [efficient micropayments](https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Contracts#Example_7:_Rapidly-adjusted_.28micro.29payments_to_a_pre-determined_party)
[0211] and on-blockchain auctions. However, this system
[0212] is inherently not color-aware; that is to say, one
[0213] cannot make a transaction of the form 'I release
[0214] this transaction output to anyone willing to pay
[0215] me one gold coin defined by the genesis H:i',
[0216] because the scripting language has no idea that a
[0217] concept of 'colors' even exists. One major
[0218] consequence of this is that, while trust-free
[0219] swapping of two different colored coins is
[0220] possible, a full decentralized exchange is not
[0221] since there is no way to place an enforceable
[0222] order to buy or sell.
[0223] 3. **Same limitations as Bitcoin** - ideally,
[0224] on-blockchain protocols would be able to support
[0225] advanced derivatives, bets and many forms of
[0226] conditional transfers. Unfortunately, colored
[0227] coins inherits the limitations of Bitcoin in terms
[0228] of the impossibility of many such arrangements.
[0230] ### Metacoins
[0232] Another concept, once again in the spirit of
[0233] sitting on top of Bitcoin much like HTTP over TCP,
[0234] is that of 'metacoins'. The concept of a metacoin
[0235] is simple: the metacoin protocol provides for a
[0236] way of encoding metacoin transaction data into the
[0237] outputs of a Bitcoin transaction, and a metacoin
[0238] node works by processing all Bitcoin transactions
[0239] and evaluating Bitcoin transactions that are valid
[0240] metacoin transactions in order to determine the
[0241] current account balances at any given time. For
[0242] example, a simple metacoin protocol might require
[0243] a transaction to have four outputs: MARKER, FROM,
[0244] TO and VALUE. MARKER would be a specific marker
[0245] address to identify a transaction as a metacoin
[0246] transaction. FROM would be the address that coins
[0247] are sent from. `TO` would be the address that
[0248] coins are sent to, and VALUE would be an address
[0249] encoding the amount sent. Because the Bitcoin
[0250] protocol is not metacoin-aware, and thus will not
[0251] reject invalid metacoin transactions, the metacoin
[0252] protocol must treat all transactions with the
[0253] first output going to MARKER as valid and react
[0254] accordingly. For example, an implementation of the
[0255] transaction processing part of the above described
[0256] metacoin protocol might look like this:
[0258]     if tx.output[0] != MARKER:
[0259]         break
[0260]     else if balance[tx.output[1]] < decode_value(tx.output[3]):
[0261]         break
[0262]     else if not tx.hasSignature(tx.output[1]):
[0263]         break
[0265]         balance[tx.output[1]] -= decode_value(tx.output[3]);
[0266]         balance[tx.output[2]] += decode_value(tx.output[3]);
[0269] The advantage of a metacoin protocol is that the
[0270] protocol can allow for more advanced transaction
[0271] types, including custom currencies, decentralized
[0272] exchange, derivatives, etc, that are impossible to
[0273] implement using the underlying Bitcoin protocol by
[0274] itself. However, metacoins on top of Bitcoin have
[0275] one major flaw: simplified payment verification,
[0276] already difficult with colored coins, is outright
[0277] impossible on a metacoin. The reason is that while
[0278] one can use SPV to determine that there is a
[0279] transaction sending 30 metacoins to address X,
[0280] that by itself does not mean that address X has 30
[0281] metacoins. What if the sender of the transaction
[0282] did not have 30 metacoins to start with and so the
[0283] transaction is invalid? Ultimately, finding out
[0284] any part of the current state requires scanning
[0285] through all transactions since the metacoin's
[0286] original launch to figure out which transactions
[0287] are valid and which ones are not. This makes it
[0288] impossible to have a truly secure client without
[0289] downloading the entire, arguably prohibitively
[0290] large, Bitcoin blockchain.
[0292] In both cases, the conclusion is as follows. The
[0293] effort to build more advanced protocols on top of
[0294] Bitcoin, like HTTP over TCP, is admirable, and is
[0295] indeed the correct way to go in terms of
[0296] implementing advanced decentralized applications.
[0297] However, the attempt to build colored coins and
[0298] metacoins on top of Bitcoin is more like building
[0299] HTTP over SMTP. The intention of SMTP was to
[0300] transfer email messages, not serve as a backbone
[0301] for generic internet communications, and one would
[0302] have had to implement many inefficient and
[0303] architecturally ugly practices in order to make it
[0304] effective. Similarly, while Bitcoin is a great
[0305] protocol for making simple transactions and
[0306] storing value, the evidence above shows that
[0307] Bitcoin is absolutely not intended to function,
[0308] and cannot function, as a base layer for financial
[0309] peer-to-peer protocols in general.
[0311] Ethereum solves the scalability issues by being
[0312] hosted on its own blockchain, and by storing a
[0313] distinct 'state tree' in each block along with a
[0314] transaction list. Each 'state tree' represents the
[0315] current state of the entire system, including
[0316] address balances and contract states. Ethereum
[0317] contracts are allowed to store data in a
[0318] persistent memory storage. This storage, combined
[0319] with the Turing-complete scripting language,
[0320] allows us to encode an entire currency inside of a
[0321] single contract, alongside countless other types
[0322] of cryptographic assets. Thus, the intention of
[0323] Ethereum is not to replace the colored coins and
[0324] metacoin protocols described above. Rather,
[0325] Ethereum intends to serve as a superior
[0326] foundational layer offering a uniquely powerful
[0327] scripting system on top of which arbitrarily
[0328] advanced contracts, currencies and other
[0329] decentralized applications can be built. If
[0330] existing colored coins and metacoin projects were
[0331] to move onto Ethereum, they would gain the
[0332] benefits of Ethereum's simplified payment
[0333] verification, the option to be compatible with
[0334] Ethereum's financial derivatives and decentralized
[0335] exchange, and the ability to work together on a
[0336] single network. With Ethereum, someone with an
[0337] idea for a new contract or transaction type that
[0338] might drastically improve the state of what can be
[0339] done with cryptocurrency would not need to start
[0340] their own coin; they could simply implement their
[0341] idea in Ethereum script code. In short, Ethereum
[0342] is a foundation for innovation.
[0345] ## Philosophy
[0347] The design behind Ethereum is intended to follow
[0348] the following principles:
[0350] 1. **Simplicity** - the Ethereum protocol should
[0351] be as simple as possible, even at the cost of some
[0352] data storage or time inefficiency. An average
[0353] programmer should ideally be able to follow and
[0354] implement the entire specification, so as to fully
[0355] realize the unprecedented democratizing potential
[0356] that cryptocurrency brings and further the vision
[0357] of Ethereum as a protocol that is open to all. Any
[0358] optimization which adds complexity should not be
[0359] included unless that optimization provides very
[0360] substantial benefit.
[0361] 2. **Universality** - a fundamental part of
[0362] Ethereum's design philosophy is that Ethereum does
[0363] not have 'features'. Instead, Ethereum provides an
[0364] internal Turing-complete scripting language, which
[0365] a programmer can use to construct any smart
[0366] contract or transaction type that can be
[0367] mathematically defined. Want to invent your own
[0368] financial derivative? With Ethereum, you can. Want
[0369] to make your own currency? Set it up as an
[0370] Ethereum contract. Want to set up a full-scale
[0371] Daemon or Skynet? You may need to have a few
[0372] thousand interlocking contracts, and be sure to
[0373] feed them generously, to do that, but nothing is
[0374] stopping you with Ethereum at your fingertips.
[0375] 3. **Modularity** - the parts of the Ethereum
[0376] protocol should be designed to be as modular and
[0377] separable as possible. Over the course of
[0378] development, our goal is to create a program where
[0379] if one was to make a small protocol modification
[0380] in one place, the application stack would continue
[0381] to function without any further modification.
[0382] Innovations such as
[0383] [Dagger](https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/%5BEnglish%5D-Dagger),
[0384] [Patricia trees](https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/%5BEnglish%5D-Patricia-Tree)
[0385] and [RLP](https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/%5BEnglish%5D-RLP)
[0386] should be implemented as separate libraries and
[0387] made to be feature-complete even if Ethereum does
[0388] not require certain features so as to make them
[0389] usable in other protocols as well. Ethereum
[0390] development should be maximally done so as to
[0391] benefit the entire cryptocurrency ecosystem, not
[0392] just itself.
[0393] 4. **Agility** - details of the Ethereum protocol
[0394] are not set in stone. Although we will be
[0395] extremely judicious about making modifications to
[0396] high-level constructs such as the
[0397] [C-like language](https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/%5BEnglish%5D-CLL)
[0398] and the address system, computational tests later
[0399] on in the development process may lead us to
[0400] discover that certain modifications to the
[0401] algorithm or scripting language will substantially
[0402] improve scalability or security. If any such
[0403] opportunities are found, we will exploit them.
[0404] 5. **Non-discrimination** - the protocol should
[0405] not attempt to actively restrict or prevent
[0406] specific categories of usage. All regulatory
[0407] mechanisms in the protocol should be designed to
[0408] directly regulate the harm and not attempt to
[0409] oppose specific undesirable applications. A
[0410] programmer can even run an infinite loop script on
[0411] top of Ethereum for as long as they are willing to
[0412] keep paying the per-computational-step transaction
[0416] ## Basic Building Blocks
[0418] At its core, Ethereum starts off as a fairly
[0419] regular memory-hard proof-of-work mined
[0420] cryptocurrency without many extra complications.
[0421] In fact, Ethereum is in some ways simpler than the
[0422] Bitcoin-based cryptocurrencies that we use today.
[0423] The concept of a transaction having multiple
[0424] inputs and outputs, for example, is gone, replaced
[0425] by a more intuitive balance-based model (to
[0426] prevent transaction replay attacks, as part of
[0427] each account balance we also store an incrementing
[0428] nonce). Sequence numbers and lock times are also
[0429] removed, and all transaction and block data is
[0430] encoded in a single format. Instead of addresses
[0431] being the RIPEMD160 hash of the SHA256 hash of the
[0432] public key prefixed with 04, addresses are simply
[0433] the last 20 bytes of the SHA3 hash of the public
[0434] key. Unlike other cryptocurrencies, which aim to
[0435] offer a large number of 'features', Ethereum
[0436] intends to take features away, and instead provide
[0437] its users with near-infinite power through an
[0438] all-encompassing mechanism known as 'contracts'.
[0440] ### Modified GHOST Implementation
[0442] The 'Greedy Heavist Observed Subtree' (GHOST)
[0443] protocol is an innovation first introduced by
[0444] Yonatan Sompolinsky and Aviv Zohar in
[0445] [December 2013](http://www.cs.huji.ac.il/~avivz/pubs/13/btc_scalability_full.pdf).
[0446] The motivation behind GHOST is that blockchains
[0447] with fast confirmation times currently suffer from
[0448] reduced security due to a high stale rate -
[0449] because blocks take a certain time to propagate
[0450] through the network, if miner A mines a block and
[0451] then miner B happens to mine another block before
[0452] miner A's block propagates to B, miner B's block
[0453] will end up wasted and will not contribute to
[0454] network security. Furthermore, there is a
[0455] centralization issue: if miner A is a mining pool
[0456] with 30% hashpower and B has 10% hashpower, A will
[0457] have a risk of producing stale blocks 70% of the
[0458] time whereas B will have a risk of producing stale
[0459] blocks 90% of the time. Thus, if the stale rate is
[0460] high, A will be substantially more efficient
[0461] simply by virtue of its size. With these two
[0462] effects combined, blockchains which produce blocks
[0463] quickly are very likely to lead to one mining pool
[0464] having a large enough percentage of the network
[0465] hashpower to have de facto control over the mining
[0466] process.
[0468] As described by Sompolinsky and Zohar, GHOST
[0469] solves the first issue of network security loss by
[0470] including stale blocks in the calculation of which
[0471] chain is the 'longest'; that is to say, not just
[0472] the parent and further ancestors of a block, but
[0473] also the stale descendants of the block's ancestor
[0474] (in Ethereum jargon, 'uncles') are added to the
[0475] calculation of which block has the largest total
[0476] proof of work backing it. To solve the second
[0477] issue of centralization bias, we go beyond the
[0478] protocol described by Sompolinsky and Zohar, and
[0479] also provide block rewards to stales: a stale
[0480] block receives 87.5% of its base reward, and the
[0481] nephew that includes the stale block receives the
[0482] remaining 12.5%. Transaction fees, however, are
[0483] not awarded to uncles.
[0485] Ethereum implements a simplified version of GHOST
[0486] which only goes down one level. Specifically, a
[0487] stale block can only be included as an uncle by
[0488] the direct child of one of its direct siblings,
[0489] and not any block with a more distant relation.
[0490] This was done for several reasons. First,
[0491] unlimited GHOST would include too many
[0492] complications into the calculation of which uncles
[0493] for a given block are valid. Second, unlimited
[0494] GHOST with compensation as used in Ethereum
[0495] removes the incentive for a miner to mine on the
[0496] main chain and not the chain of a public attacker.
[0497] Finally, calculations show that single-level GHOST
[0498] has over 80% of the benefit of unlimited GHOST,
[0499] and provides a stale rate comparable to the 2.5
[0500] minute Litecoin even with a 40-second block time.
[0501] However, we will be conservative and still retain
[0502] a Primecoin-like 60-second block time because
[0503] individual blocks may take a longer time to
[0504] verify.
[0507] ### Ethereum Client P2P Protocol
[0509] **P2P Protocol**
[0510] ![40b9c7c233df7d49d672fc23205294f40529fda9b5d1887d1718ccd1fb9b14d3](img/minerchart.png)
[0512] The Ethereum client P2P protocol is a fairly
[0513] standard cryptocurrency protocol, and can just as
[0514] easily be used for any other cryptocurrency; the
[0515] only modification is the introduction of the GHOST
[0516] protocol described above. The Ethereum client will
[0517] be mostly reactive; if not provoked, the only
[0518] thing the client will do by itself is have the
[0519] networking daemon maintain connections and
[0520] periodically send a message asking for blocks
[0521] whose parent is the current block. However, the
[0522] client will also be more powerful. Unlike
[0523] bitcoind, which only stores a limited amount of
[0524] data about the blockchain, the Ethereum client
[0525] will also act as a fully functional backend for a
[0526] block explorer.
[0528] When the client reads a message, it will perform
[0529] the following steps:
[0531] 1. Hash the data, and check if the data with that
[0532] hash has already been received. If so, exit.
[0533] 2. Determine the data type. If the data is a
[0534] transaction, if the transaction is valid add it to
[0535] the local transaction list, process it onto the
[0536] current block and publish it to the network. If
[0537] the data item is a message, respond to it. If the
[0538] data item is a block, go to step 3.
[0539] 3. Check if the parent of the block is already
[0540] stored in the database. If it is not, exit.
[0541] 4. Check if the proof of work on the block header
[0542] and all block headers in the 'uncle list' is
[0543] valid. If any are not, exit.
[0544] 5. Check if every block header in the 'uncle list'
[0545] in the block has the block's parent's parent as
[0546] its own parent. If any is not, exit. Note that
[0547] uncle block headers do not need to be in the
[0548] database; they just need to have the correct

[0812] ### Mining algorithm
[0814] One highly desirable property in mining algorithms
[0815] is resistance to optimization through specialized
[0816] hardware. Originally, Bitcoin was conceived as a
[0817] highly democratic currency, allowing anyone to
[0818] participate in the mining process with a CPU. In
[0819] 2010, however, much faster miners exploiting the
[0820] rapid parallelization offered by graphics
[0821] processing units (GPUs) rapidly took over,
[0822] increasing network hashpower by a factor of 100
[0823] and leaving CPUs essentially in the dust. In 2013,
[0824] a further category of specialized hardware,
[0825] application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs)
[0826] outcompeted the GPUs in turn, achieving another
[0827] 100x speedup by using chips fabricated for the
[0828] sole purpose of computing SHA256 hashes. Today, it
[0829] is virtually impossible to mine without first
[0830] purchasing a mining device from one of these
[0831] companies, and some people are concerned that in
[0832] 5-10 years' time mining will be entirely dominated
[0833] by large centralized corporations such as AMD and
[0834] Intel.
[0836] To date, the main way of achieving this goal has
[0837] been 'memory-hardness', constructing proof of work
[0838] algorithms that require not only a large number of
[0839] computations, but also a large amount of memory,
[0840] to validate, thereby making highly parallelized
[0841] specialized hardware implementations less
[0842] effective. There have been several implementations
[0843] of memory-hard proof of work, all of which have
[0844] their flaws:
[0846] * **Scrypt** - Scrypt is a function which is
[0847] designed to take 128 KB of memory
[0848] [to compute](https://litecoin.info/User:Iddo/Comparison_between_Litecoin_and_Bitcoin#SHA256_mining_vs_scrypt_mining).
[0849] The algorithm essentially works by filling a
[0850] memory array with hashes, and then computing
[0851] intermediate values and finally a result based on
[0852] the values in the memory array. However, the 128
[0853] KB parameter is a very weak threshold, and ASICs
[0854] for Litecoin are
[0855] [already under development](https://axablends.com/merchants-accepting-bitcoin/litecoin-discussion/litecoin-scrypt-asic-miners/).
[0856] Furthermore, there is a natural limit to how much
[0857] memory hardness with Scrypt can be tweaked up to
[0858] achieve, as the verification process takes just as
[0859] much memory, and just as much computation, as one
[0860] round of the mining process.
[0861] * **Birthday attacks** - the idea behind
[0862] birthday-based proofs of work is simple: find
[0863] values xn, i, j such that i < k, j < k and
[0864] abs(H(data+xn+i) - H(data+xn+j)) < 2^256 / d^2.
[0865] The d parameter sets the computational difficulty
[0866] of finding a block, and the k parameter sets the
[0867] memory hardness. Any birthday algorithm must
[0868] somehow store all computations of H(data+xn+i) in
[0869] memory so that future computations can be compared
[0870] against them. Here, computation is memory-hard,
[0871] but verification is memory-easy, allowing for
[0872] extreme memory hardness without compromising the
[0873] ease of verification. However, the algorithm is
[0874] problematic for two reasons. First, there is a
[0875] time-memory tradeoff attack where users 2x less
[0876] memory can compensate with 2x more computational
[0877] power, so its memory hardness is not absolute.
[0878] Second, it may be easy to build specialized
[0879] hardware devices for the problem, especially once
[0880] one moves beyond traditional chip and processor
[0881] architecture and into various classes of
[0882] hardware-based hash tables or probabilistic analog
[0883] computing.
[0884] * **Dagger** - the idea behind
[0885] [Dagger](https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/%5BEnglish%5D-Dagger),
[0886] an in-house algorithm developed by the Ethereum
[0887] team, is to have an algorithm that is similar to
[0888] Scrypt, but which is specially designed so that
[0889] each individual nonce only depends on a small
[0890] portion of the data tree that gets built up for
[0891] each group of ~10 million nonces. Computing nonces
[0892] with any reasonable level of efficiency requires
[0893] building up the entire tree, taking up over 100 MB
[0894] of memory, whereas verifying a nonce only takes
[0895] about 100 KB. However, Dagger-style algorithms are
[0896] vulnerable to devices that have multiple
[0897] computational circuits sharing the same memory,
[0898] and although this threat can be mitigated it is
[0899] arguably impossible to fully remove.
[0901] One of the key ingredients in a standard
[0902] cryptocurrency is the idea of proof of work. A
[0903] proof of work, in general, is a function which is
[0904] hard to compute, but easy to verify, allowing it
[0905] to serve as a probabilistic cryptographic proof of
[0906] the quantity of computational resources controlled
[0907] by a given node. In Bitcoin, and Ethereum, this
[0908] mechanism is intimately tied in with the
[0909] blockchain: every block requires a proof of work
[0910] of some prespecified difficulty level in order to
[0911] be valid, and in the event of multiple competing
[0912] blockchains the chain with the largest total
[0913] quantity of proof of work is considered to be
[0914] valid. Thus, in order to reverse a transaction, an
[0915] attacker needs to start a new fork of the
[0916] blockchain from before the block the transaction
[0917] was confirmed in, and then apply more
[0918] computational power than the rest of the network
[0919] combined in order to overtake the legitimate fork.
[0921] However, one of the key requirements for a proof
[0922] of work algorithm to, well, work is
[0923] decentralization. If the proof of work algorithm
[0924] is designed in such a way that the proof of work
[0925] computation can only be efficiently done by
[0926] entities with the millions of dollars of capital
[0927] required to develop specialized hardware, then the
[0928] number of participants in the process will be
[0929] small enough that it will be possible for the
[0930] majority of miners to conspire and reverse
[0931] transactions. Alternatively, if the proof of work
[0932] algorithm encourages miners to outsource their
[0933] block verification work to centralized entities,
[0934] then that is another way that centralization can
[0935] creep in, and it would be the mining pools that
[0936] have the potential to form conspiracies. Ideally,
[0937] proof of work algorithms should solve both of
[0938] those problems.

[1100] ### Block Rewards and Limits
[1102] A miner receives three kinds of rewards: a static
[1103] block reward for producing a block, fees from
[1104] transactions, and nephew/uncle rewards as
[1105] described in the GHOST section above. The miner
[1106] will receive 100% of the block reward and
[1107] transaction fees for themselves. As described in
[1108] the GHOST section, uncles only receive 87.5% of
[1109] their block reward, with the remaining 12.5% going
[1110] to the including nephew; the transaction fees from
[1111] the stale block do not go to anyone.
[1113] The default approach is to have no mandatory fees,
[1114] allowing miners to include any transactions that
[1115] they deem profitable to include. This approach has
[1116] been received very favorably in the Bitcoin
[1117] community particularly because it is
[1118] 'market-based' - that is, there is a market with
[1119] miners on one side and transaction senders on the
[1120] other where supply and demand determine the price.
[1121] However, the problem with this line of reasoning
[1122] is that transaction processing is not a market;
[1123] although it is intuitively attractive to construe
[1124] transaction processing as a service that the miner
[1125] is making the effort to offer to transaction
[1126] senders that needs to be paid for at an
[1127] agreed-upon rate, in reality every transaction
[1128] that a single miner includes needs to be processed
[1129] by every node in the network, so the external
[1130] costs of transaction processing borne by the
[1131] network, which has no say in whether or not a
[1132] transaction takes place, are thousands of times
[1133] higher than the internal costs borne by the miner.
[1135] However, as it turns out this flaw in the
[1136] market-based mechanism, when given a particular
[1137] inaccurate simplifying assumption, magically
[1138] cancels itself out. The argument is as follows.
[1139] Suppose that:
[1141] 1. The mining block reward is `B`.
[1142] 2. A transaction leads to `k` operations, offering
[1143] the reward `kR` to any miner that includes it
[1144] where `R` is set by the sender and `k` and `R` are
[1145] visible to the miner beforehand.
[1146] 3. An operation has a processing cost of `C` to
[1147] any node (ie. all nodes have equal efficiency)
[1148] 4. There are `N` mining nodes, each with exactly
[1149] equal processing power (ie. `1/N` of total)
[1150] 5. No non-mining full nodes exist.
[1152] A miner would be willing to process a transaction
[1153] if the expected reward is greater than the cost.
[1154] The expected reward is `kR/N` since the miner has
[1155] a `1/N` chance of processing the next block. The
[1156] cost is simply `kC`. Thus, the miner is willing to
[1157] process transactions where:
[1160]     kR > kNC
[1163] Note that `R` is the per-operation fee, and `NC`
[1164] is the cost to the entire network together of
[1165] processing an operation. Hence, miners have the
[1166] incentive to include only those transactions for
[1167] which the total utilitarian benefit exceeds the
[1168] cost. However, there are three important
[1169] deviations from those assumptions in reality:
[1171] 1. The miner does pay a higher cost to process the
[1172] transaction than the other verifying nodes, since
[1173] the extra verification time delays block
[1174] propagation and thus increases the chance the
[1175] block will become a stale.
[1176] 2. There do exist nonmining full nodes.
[1177] 3. The mining power distribution may end up
[1178] radically inegalitarian in practice.
[1179] 4. Speculators, political enemies and crazies
[1180] whose utility function includes causing harm to
[1181] the network do exist, and they can cleverly set up
[1182] contracts where their cost is much lower than the
[1183] cost paid by other verifying nodes.
[1185] (1) provides a tendency for the miner to include
[1186] fewer transactions, and (2) increases `NC`; hence,
[1187] these two effects at least partially cancel each
[1188] other out. (3) and (4) are the major issue; to
[1189] solve them we simply institute a floating cap: no
[1190] block can have more operations than 150% of the
[1191] long-term exponential moving average (exact figure
[1192] subject to change pending further economic
[1193] analysis).
[1195] ## Contracts
[1197] In Ethereum, there are two types of entities that
[1198] can generate and receive transactions: actual
[1199] people (or bots, as cryptographic protocols cannot
[1200] distinguish between the two) and contracts. A
[1201] contract is essentially an automated agent that
[1202] lives on the Ethereum network, has an Ethereum
[1203] address and balance, and can send and receive
[1204] transactions. A contract is 'activated' every time
[1205] someone sends a transaction to it, at which point
[1206] it runs its code, perhaps modifying its internal
[1207] state or even sending some transactions, and then
[1208] shuts down. The 'code' for a contract is written
[1209] in a special-purpose low-level language consisting
[1210] of a stack, which is not persistent, 2^256 memory
[1211] entries, which are also not persistent, and 2^256
[1212] storage entries which constitute the contract's
[1213] permanent state. Note that Ethereum users will not
[1214] need to code in this low-level stack language; we
[1215] are providing a simple
[1216] [C-Like language](https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/%5BEnglish%5D-CLL)
[1217] with variables, expressions, conditionals, arrays
[1218] and while loops, and provide a compiler down to
[1219] Ethereum script code.

[1873] As mentioned above, the intent is not for people
[1874] to write scripts directly in Ethereum script code;
[1875] rather, we will release compilers to generate ES
[1876] from higher-level languages. The first supported
[1877] language will likely be the simple
[1878] [C-like language](https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/%5BEnglish%5D-CLL)
[1879] used in the descriptions above, and the second
[1880] will be a more complete first-class-function
[1881] language with support for arrays and
[1882] arbitrary-length strings. Compiling the C-like
[1883] language is fairly simple as far as compilers go:
[1884] variables can be assigned a memory index, and
[1885] compiling an arithmetic expression essentially
[1886] involves converting it to reverse Polish notation
[1888] PUSH 0 MLOAD PUSH 1 MLOAD ADD MUL`). First-class
[1889] function languages are more involved due to
[1890] variable scoping, but the problem is nevertheless
[1891] tractable. The likely solution will be to maintain
[1892] a linked list of stack frames in memory, giving
[1893] each stack frame N memory slots where N is the
[1894] total number of distinct variable names in the
[1895] program. Variable access will consist of searching
[1896] down the stack frame list until one frame contains
[1897] a pointer to the variable, copying the pointer to
[1898] the top stack frame for memoization purposes, and
[1899] returning the value at the pointer. However, these
[1900] are longer term concerns; compilation is separate
[1901] from the actual protocol, and so it will be
[1902] possible to continue to research compilation
[1903] strategies long after the network is set running.
[1908] In Bitcoin, there are no mandatory transaction
[1909] fees. Transactions can optionally include fees
[1910] which are paid to miners, and it is up to the
[1911] miners to decide what fees they are willing to
[1912] accept. In Bitcoin, such a mechanism is already
[1913] imperfect; the need for a 1 MB block size limit
[1914] alongside the fee mechanism shows this all too
[1915] well. In Ethereum, because of its
[1916] Turing-completeness, a purely voluntary fee system
[1917] would be catastrophic. Instead, Ethereum will have
[1918] a system of mandatory fees, including a
[1919] transaction fee and six fees for contract
[1920] computations. The fees are currently set to:
[1922] * TXFEE (100x) - fee for sending a transaction
[1923] * NEWCONTRACTFEE (100x) - fee for creating a new
[1924] contract, not including the storage fee for each
[1925] item in script code
[1926] * STEPFEE (1x) - fee for every computational step
[1927] after the first sixteen in contract execution
[1928] * STORAGEFEE (5x) - per-byte fee for adding to
[1929] contract storage. The storage fee is the only fee
[1930] that is not paid to a miner, and is refunded when
[1931] storage used by a contract is reduced or removed.
[1932] * DATAFEE (20x) - fee for accessing or setting a
[1933] contract's memory from inside that contract
[1934] * EXTROFEE (40x) - fee for accessing memory from
[1935] another contract inside a contract
[1936] * CRYPTOFEE (20x) - fee for using any of the
[1937] cryptographic operations
[1940] The coefficients will be revised as more hard data
[1941] on the relative computational cost of each
[1942] operation becomes available. The hardest part will
[1943] be setting the value of x. There are currently two
[1944] main solutions that we are considering:
[1946] * Make x inversely proportional to the square root
[1947] of the difficulty, so x = floor(10^21 /
[1948] floor(difficulty ^ 0.5)). This automatically
[1949] adjusts fees down as the value of ether goes up,
[1950] and adjusts fees down as computers get more
[1951] powerful due to Moore's Law.
[1952] * Use proof of stake voting to determine the fees.
[1953] In theory, stakeholders do not benefit directly
[1954] from fees going up or down, so their incentives
[1955] would be to make the decision that would maximize
[1956] the value of the network.
[1958] A hybrid solution is also possible, using proof of
[1959] stake voting, but with the inverse square root
[1960] mechanism as an initial policy.
[1963] ## Conclusion
[1965] The Ethereum protocol's design philosophy is in
[1966] many ways the opposite from that taken by many
[1967] other cryptocurrencies today. Other
[1968] cryptocurrencies aim to add complexity and
[1969] increase the number of 'features'; Ethereum, on
[1970] the other hand, takes features away. The protocol
[1971] does not 'support' multisignature transactions,
[1972] multiple inputs and outputs, hash codes, lock
[1973] times or many other features that even Bitcoin
[1974] provides. Instead, all complexity comes from a
[1975] universal, Turing-complete scripting language,
[1976] which can be used to build up literally any
[1977] feature that is mathematically describable through
[1978] the contract mechanism. As a result, we have a
[1979] protocol with unique potential; rather than being
[1980] a closed-ended, single-purpose protocol intended
[1981] for a specific array of applications in data
[1982] storage, gambling or finance, Ethereum is
[1983] open-ended by design, and we believe that it is
[1984] extremely well-suited to serving as a foundational
[1985] layer for a very large number of both financial
[1986] and non-financial protocols in the years to come.
